The highest price a company should be willing to pay for another is the one that makes the $\operatorname{NVP}$ of the merger zero. In other words, where the company does not earn but no loses money. Certainly in this case other reasons will motivate the merger. 

Then, let's calculate the price per share by substituting the $\operatorname{NVP}$ formula from the previous section. 

$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{NPV}
=
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Current}\\ 
\text{cash flow}
\end{array}
+
\frac{\mathrm{CF}^1}{ (1+r)^1}+\frac{\mathrm{CF}^2}{(1+r)^2}+\frac{\mathrm{CF}^3 }{(1+r)^3}+\frac{\mathrm{CF}^4}{(1+r)^4}+\frac{\mathrm{CF}^5}{(1+r)^5}
\end{equation}
$$

Let´s consider $\operatorname{NPV} = 0$:
$$
\begin{align*}
0 &= \text{Current cash flow} + \$167,665,903\\[10pt]
\text{Current cash flow} &= -\$167,665,903
\end{align*}
$$
The current cash flow or Cash flow of year zero should be $-\$167,665,903$ to make the $\operatorname{NPV}$ zero.

Let's recall that current cash flow is the difference between the value that the company $A$ receives from the merger and the cost of the acquisition: 
$$
\text{Current cash flow} 
= 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Value Company $A$}\\ 
\text{receives after merger} 
\end{array}
-
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Cost to Firm $A$}\\ 
\text{of the acquisition}
\end{array}
$$

Also, the cost of acquisition in the case of a cash acquisition is the result of multiplying the price per share by the number of shares outstanding. 

Then, from the previous section we know that: 
$$\text{Current cash flow} = \$55,000,000 – (\text{Price per share}\times \text{Shares outstanding})$$

Let's substitute the current cash flow needed for $\operatorname{NPV}= 0$:
$$
\begin{align*}
 -\$167,665,903 &= \$55,000,000 – (\text{Price per share} \times 8,000,000)\\[10pt]
\text{Price per share} \times 8,000,000 &= \$167,665,903 + \$55,000,000\\[10pt]
\text{Price per share} &=\frac{ \$222,665,903}{ 8,000,000}\\[10pt]
\text{Price per share} &= \$27.833237875
\end{align*}
$$

***<span style="color: #4257B2">The highest price per share that Birdie should be willing to pay for Hybrid is $27.83</span>***.
